# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alex-pacheco-activist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The **1986 Hvalur sinkings** occurred in Iceland's Reykjavík harbour in November 1986, when anti-whaling activists from the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society sank the unoccupied whaling vessels, *Hvalur 6* and *Hvalur 7*, and sabotaged a whale processing station in Hvalfjörður.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The ships were two of the nation's fleet of four and were eventually raised, but have not gone on a whale hunt since and were dragged onto dry land.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Repairs have still not yet been made to the ships some 36 years later.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The factory was the country's only processing facility.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The incident was an attempt by animal-rights activists to disrupt Iceland's whaling industry after the country circumvented a commercial ban on the practice to conduct research.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] No one was injured but the attack caused $2 million worth of damage to the ships, $2 million worth of damage to the processing plant, and damage to the whale meat freezer in the processing plant spoiled $4 million worth of whale meat.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The perpetrators, Rod Coronado and David Howitt, were able to escape the scene via a flight to Luxembourg.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] A moratorium on commercial whaling was implemented by the International Whaling Commission in January 1986; the ban allowed for scientific whaling to continue.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The Sea Shepherd Conservation Society direct-action environmentalist group wished to intervene in the whaling continued by Iceland, Norway, the Soviet Union, Japan, and the Faroe Islands.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The government of Iceland believed that taking 120 whales in 1986 for research was vital to its fishing industry.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] In June 1986, the plan was formulated to sabotage Iceland's whaling industry with an emphasis on causing as much economic damage as possible with the intent to act when there was no threat to human life.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The operation was delayed due to a summit in Reykjavík between the governments of the United States and the Soviet Union that October.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] One of the perpetrators, Rod Coronado, was also allegedly involved in an attack on Faroese whalers in June.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Sea Shepherd activists Rod Coronado and David Howitt flew into Reykjavík in October 1986.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Howitt has also been named as David Howard, Nick Taylor or Martin Braidley.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The pair stayed at a youth hostel and began covertly investigating the local whaling industry and it has been reported that they posed as tourists and took jobs at a fish factory.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] On 8 November, they traveled 50 miles to the nation's only whale processing station in Hvalfjörður, where they broke in at 8:00 pm.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Sledgehammers, wrenches, and other common tools were used to systematically destroy computers, power generators, machinery, and windows.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The large refrigeration unit used to freeze the season's catch was destroyed beyond repair and documentation at the facility was doused with acid.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The main factory and two smaller buildings were left inoperable.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Coronado and Howitt then returned to Reykjavik during the early hours of 9 November where three of the country's four whalers were moored.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] They had no problem in boarding the boats from the dock, since the vessels were unguarded.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The saltwater cooling valves in the engine room were opened at around 5:00 am, causing the ships to flood and sink within half an hour.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The third whaler, *Hvalur 8*, was not attacked since a watchman was aboard while the fourth, *Hvalur 9*, was in drydock.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The police did not arrive at the harbor until 7:00 am, and the attackers were able to flee the country via a 7:45 am flight to Luxembourg.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] They were subjects of a routine traffic stop en route to the airport but the police did not suspect them of any wrongdoing and let them continue on their way.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] In November the two 430-ton whaling vessels were raised from the harbor floor by a salvaging company.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] According to the whaling company, the attack caused $2 million worth of damage.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Not long after this, Paul Watson took full responsibility for the operation, saying that he had planned it, had picked the team, and had seen that the attackers did their job.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Prime Minister Steingrímur Hermannsson announced that Iceland was trying to find the men and criticised the police for the initial delay that allowed them to escape.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Watson travelled to Iceland in 1988 to face prosecution as Sea Shepherd's leader where he was detained for 24 hours before being deported without cause.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] A spokesperson for Iceland's largest whaling company told *The New Yorker* that Watson is *persona non grata* in the country.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] With their escape, Coronado and Howitt have never been charged with any wrong-doing in Iceland.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Both have admitted responsibility but the statute of limitations for the act has passed.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] As a result of this incident, the International Whaling Commission revoked Sea Shepherd's observer status.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Most environmentalists, though critical of Iceland's stand, distanced themselves from Sea Shepherd's violent tactics.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] An article in *The New Yorker* said that it was "an act of sabotage that many conservationists believe helped turn Icelandic public opinion against the cause of saving whales".
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The international reactions were negative.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] The action had various descriptions such as an act of vandalism, an act of terrorism or the act of madmen.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] At the time of the incident, Iceland, Greenpeace International, and some media commentators in Iceland and North America referred to the sabotage as "terrorism" or "terrorist".
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Coronado responded to these comparisons by arguing that the sabotage was "the farthest thing from terrorism" and that whaling itself constituted terrorism.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] In a Canadian newspaper the incident was also cited as one of the first steps taken by Coronado in becoming "a new breed of terrorist" who went on to wage a wide-ranging battle for animal rights as a member of the Animal Liberation Front.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/1986-hvalur-sinkings] Coronado has rejected the "terrorist" label as "garbage", because beginning with the *Hvalur* sinkings, he says that he has always taken care that no one is physically hurt by his acts of sabotage.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco first crewed with Captain Paul Watson in 1979 on the ship *Sea Shepherd* across the Atlantic Ocean, during a campaign of opposition to the *Sierra*, a Portuguese pirate whaling ship.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Both *The Sea Shepherd* and the *Sierra* were sunk after being seized by the Portuguese authorities.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco came to wider public attention in 1981 for his role, along with Ingrid Newkirk, in what became known as the Silver Spring monkeys case, a campaign to release 17 crab-eating macaques who were undergoing experiments in the Institute for Behavioral Research in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Filmmaker Oliver Stone writes that the political campaign to save the monkeys gave birth to the animal rights movement in the United States.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco was born in Joliet, Illinois, but moved to Mexico with his family when he was very young, where he and his two siblings were raised near the ocean by his Mexican father, a physician, and his mother, an American nurse.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Kathy Snow Guillermo writes in *Monkey Business* (1993) that Pacheco's early life was filled with animals; bats lived in the rubber trees in his front yard, snakes slept behind nearby rocks, and fishermen regularly dragged dolphins out of the water onto the beach.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Instead of animals being killed for food in slaughterhouses, pigs, oxen, chickens, and turkeys were frequently killed in front of him.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The family left Mexico when Pacheco was in junior high, and moved between Ohio, Indiana, and Illinois.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He bought turtles and birds from pet stores, and a baby crab-eating macaque, whom he called Chi Chi and who would perch on his shoulder as he walked around the house.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He attended a Catholic university in Ohio, intending to enter the priesthood, but while in Canada in his first year at the university, he visited a friend who worked at a meat-packing plant.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Guillermo writes that he was shocked by the sight of two men throwing a newborn calf, cut from the uterus of its slaughtered mother, into a dumpster.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Later in the week, a friend gave him a copy of Peter Singer's *Animal Liberation*, and he returned to Ohio as a vegetarian.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] His heart was no longer in becoming a priest, and he decided to attend Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio and devote himself to helping what he called "other-than-human beings".
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] At university, Pacheco organized campaigns against the use of leghold traps and castrating pigs and cattle without anesthetic.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Guillermo writes that, as Ohio is an agricultural state, his activism met with stiff opposition and the occasional anonymous telephone call threatening to blow his head off.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In 1979, he attended a talk in Columbus, Ohio, by Cleveland Amory of the *Saturday Review*, who was also the founder of the Fund for Animals, which funded the anti-whaling vessel the *Sea Shepherd*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He sought Amory out after the talk and volunteered.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The Silver Spring monkeys case began in 1981, when Pacheco took a job as a volunteer inside the Institute for Behavioral Research in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Edward Taub, a neuroscientist, was cutting sensory ganglia that supplied nerves to the fingers, hands, arms, and legs of 17 macaque monkeys – a process known as "deafferentation" – so that the monkeys could not feel them.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] (Some of them had had their entire spinal columns deafferented.) Taub used restraint and electric shock to force the monkeys to use the limbs they could not feel.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He discovered that, when motivated by extreme hunger or the desire to avoid electric shock, they could be induced to use their deafferented limbs.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The research led in part to the discovery of neuroplasticity within the primate motor system and a new therapy for stroke victims called constraint-induced movement therapy that helped restore the use of affected limbs.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco reported Taub for violations of animal cruelty laws based on the animals' living conditions.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Police raided the lab, seized the monkeys and charged Taub with 119 counts of animal cruelty and failure to provide adequate veterinary care, the first such charges brought in the United States against a research scientist.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] 113 charges were dismissed at the first court hearing.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Taub was initially convicted on six misdemeanor counts of failure to provide adequate veterinary care.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Five convictions were dismissed after a second trial, and the final conviction was overturned on appeal when the court ruled that Maryland's Prevention of Cruelty to Animals law did not apply to researchers.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The legal battle for custody of the monkeys, following their removal by PETA, reached the United States Supreme Court.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] It was the first animal-rights case to do so, though the newly formed PETA ultimately failed in its battle to secure the animals' release.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The proceedings, which lasted years, generated a large amount of publicity for PETA, transforming it from what Ingrid Newkirk called "five people in a basement" into a national movement.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In 1992, Pacheco and a staffer went to the Hawaiian island of Molokai and destroyed several hundred wire snares that were causing pigs and goats to die slowly of strangulation, starvation, and dehydration.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The traps had been set by the Nature Conservancy in an effort to preserve native species by killing non-native species.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] After this was publicized, the Nature Conservancy discontinued the trapping.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In July 1983, *The New York Times* reported that Pacheco was responsible for Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger halting Pentagon plans to shoot dogs in a "wound laboratory" at a military medical facility near Washington, D.C.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco had learned about the project and notified both Congress and *The Washington Post*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Weinberger had a collie, and when he read the article, he immediately banned the use of dogs in the experiments.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Two days later, he also ordered the Pentagon to review the plans and suspend the shooting of pigs, goats, and other animals until the review was completed.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco continued to raise public awareness of the issue through protests.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He also worked with Congressional contacts and the media in order to convince the military to make the change permanent and include other facilities and other species.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In November 1983, Congressional representatives instructed the Defense Department not to use dogs and cats in any wound laboratories, and the policy went into effect in January 1984.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In late 1984, after continued public pressure and completion of the review ordered by Secretary Weinberger, the secretaries of the Army and Air Force banned the use of dogs and cats not just in wound labs, but in all biomedical and clinical research under their control.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In late 1983, Pacheco went to Falls County, Texas, to investigate reports of horses dying in fields.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] At least 14,000 horses had been gathered by a company called Horses Unlimited, which planned to fatten them for slaughter and sale in Europe as horsemeat.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Instead, 2,000 horses died of starvation, and one third of the rest suffered from severe malnutrition.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco and others tried to aid the horses but were threatened with arrest by Falls County authorities, PETA told reporters.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He took his investigation and evidence of cruelty to the national media in early 1984.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] State investigators called it "one of the biggest cases of animal abuse in the state's history", and Jacy Reese Anthis described it as "the first modern undercover investigation of farmed animal abuse" in his 2018 book *The End of Animal Farming*.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] As a result of his efforts, Pacheco was brought before a grand jury on criminal charges.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He was represented by well-known defense attorney Richard "Racehorse" Haynes, and the charges were dropped.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The same month, the slaughter operation closed down permanently.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In May 1984, Pacheco compiled a 30-minute video called *Unnecessary Fuss* based on 60 hours of videotapes taken from the Pennsylvania Head Injury Lab by the underground organization Animal Liberation Front.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The videos, made by the researchers, showed baboons receiving severe head and neck injuries from a head-acceleration machine.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The videos also included footage of the researchers laughing at injured, brain-damaged animals.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] After nearly a year of other efforts to stop the federal government from continuing to fund this laboratory, in July 1985 Pacheco led approximately 100 activists in a sit-in at the headquarters of the National Institutes of Health, the federal agency funding the experiments.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The sit-in lasted 4 days, after which Secretary of Health and Human Services Margaret Heckler publicly announced the termination of funding for the $14 million Head Injury Laboratory at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] During his 20-year tenure as chairman of PETA, Pacheco was involved in bringing public attention to the way animals are treated in cosmetic tests and in urging companies to abandon this practice.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] These campaigns resulted in major companies such as Avon, Revlon, and Benetton ending animal tests on products sold in the U.S., and hundreds of other companies pledging to do the same.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] He was also involved in informing the public about the treatment of animals used for fur.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The publicity by PETA was considered by the media, the public, and some in the fur industry to have caused a decline in fur sales.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In 2010, Alex Pacheco founded 600 Million Dogs with the mission to develop safe veterinary formulas to permanently end the number one cause of suffering and death for dogs and cats worldwide—dog and cat overpopulation.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The first formulas in development are Spay and Neuter Cookies, which are being designed to safely sterilize strays—without surgery.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The objective is to end the cycle of suffering for the tens of millions of stray cats in the U.S. and end the cycle of suffering for the 600 million stray dogs worldwide, who give birth to over one billion stray pups each year.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The organization is also dedicated to alleviating the plight of the 29 million people who are treated for rabies each year, and preventing the deaths of the 59,000 people who die from rabies each year.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] The Peace Abbey, of Sherborn, Massachusetts, awarded Alex Pacheco the Courage of Conscience award in 1995.
[src:alex-pacheco-activist/alex-pacheco-activist] In 2001, Pacheco was inducted into the US Animal Rights Hall of Fame.
